[𓊪](𓊪)[𓏏](𓏏)[𓇯](𓇯)𓀭 |Potair|Sky Father|𓊪=P 𓏏=T 𓇯=Air  
[𓇋](𓇋)𓏏𓆑𓀀 | ★feathav  | father|[𓇋](𓇋)=(f)e 𓏏=t 𓆑=v  
[𓅓](𓅓)[𓅱](𓅱)[𓏏](𓏏)[𓅐](𓅐) |Muta (Gaia)|Mother (Nature)| 𓅓=M 𓅱=u 𓏏=t  
[𓈖](𓈖)[𓏏](𓏏)[𓂋](𓂋)[𓏯](𓏯)[𓅐](𓅐)| Nature| (Mother) vulture |𓈖=N 𓏏=T 𓂋=R  

Over the course of 3000 years, many dialects and some conquests, the precise sound of vowels is probably unrecoverably lost. Its rendering in transcritions is therefore a matter of convention, suggestion or artistic choice but should be ignored for linguistic studies. Which would make some endeavours pretty hopeless if it wasn't for the existence of large clusters. For instance gab, kaf,… in semitic languages means hand and there a hundreds of words with g-b k-f c-v stems which all mean something related to 'cover'. An open mind would consider that this strong root is connected with IE variants (Koffer...), and maybe even with caput(head) geben give …

