We know very little about how the vowels between consonants actually sounded like, often they are omitted and only a(r) (f)e (y)i and (w)u(n) are used regularily. 

That looks more dire than it sounds: Sometimes the nature of a vowel can be estimated from context. 
𓈖 'n' is somewhat related to nile, nau/navi(water) nun(fish) nar(fish) eliminating at least some parts of the vowel manifold. But then it could also be related to mem(water) mnemn meander mar mwater.

For exampel [[𓍢]] 𓏲 (meaning hundred) can be read as round wound houn(dreh), which gives whr plus a ou sound. related words wend wind bend band have other signs, though they appear together.

On the other hand some vowels appear to have consonant which are lost in the reconstruction, leading to bizarre words like a.a.a  
We try to contribute to the reconstruction of some phonetics, though some words must be viewed as working hypothesis.

Using the Egyptian [alphabet](Alphabet) in its late form, which is preserved to us by comparisons to the derived coptic and demotic languages, as well as comparisons to greek and semitic languages. {[read](Alphabet) if you are German}

